revision.text:
On October 3, 1980, the eve of [[Simchat Torah]], a bomb went off outside the [[Union Libérale Israélite de France]] synagogue on Rue Copernic, Paris. Four people were killed and more than forty injured. The bomb, consisting of about {{convert|10|kg|lb}} of [[Semtex]] explosives, had been hidden in the saddlebags of a motorcycle parked outside the synagogue. It went off at 6:38 PM, shortly before the end of services. None of those killed were members of the congregation.<ref name=cobb1>{{cite news|last=Cobb|first=Chris|title=Paris blast, Part 1: The Explosion|url=http://www.ottawacitizen.com/opinion/Special+feature+EXPLOSION/3786367/story.html|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=November 9, 2010}}</ref>
==Aftermath and investigation== After the attack then-Prime Minister [[Raymond Barre]] sparked allegations of anti-semitism by describing the bombing as “a heinous act against Jews in a synagogue that struck four innocent Frenchmen crossing the street”&mdash;a comment which seemed to imply that the synagogue's members were neither innocent nor truly French.<ref name=cobb2>{{cite news|last=Cobb|first=Chris|title=Paris blast, Part 2: The Aftermath|url=http://www.ottawacitizen.com/business/Special+Series+AFTERMATH/3789865/story.html|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|date=November 9, 2010}}</ref><ref name="wistrich">{{cite book|last=Wistrich|first=Robert|title=A Lethal Obsession: Anti-Semitism from Antiquity to the Global Jihad|publisher=Random House|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Lzs48d3tudsC&pg=PT370&dq=barre+%22innocent+frenchmen%22&hl=en&ei=mAB9TfCSGcfVgQeWkrnFBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=barre%20%22innocent%20frenchmen%22&f=false|authorlink=Robert Wistrich|date=2010}}</ref>
French police initially suspected that the attack had been carried out by [[neo-Nazis]], but later attributed it to the [[PFLP]] or one of its offshoots.<ref name=cobb3>{{cite news|last=Cobb|first=Chris|title=Paris blast, Part 3: The Investigation|url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/news/Special+Series+INVESTIGATION/3792139/story.html|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|date=November 9, 2010}}</ref> In 2008 France began seeking the extradition of [[Hassan Diab]], a Lebanese-born Canadian citizen, in connection with the bombing.<ref name=Star>{{cite news | title = Canadian held in Paris synagogue bombing | publisher = The Toronto Star | date = November 14, 2008 | url =http://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/536814 }}</ref><ref name=Globe>{{cite news | title = File on 1980 Paris bombing revealed | publisher = The Globe and Mail | date = November 20, 2008 | url = http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/article723907.ece }}</ref>
==Subsequent attacks== The bombing was the first of a string of attacks against Jews in Europe. On August 29, 1981, a synagogue in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], was attacked by [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] gunmen, who killed two people and wounded 30 in the [[1981 Vienna synagogue attack]]. On October 20, 1981, also the eve of Simchat Torah, three people were killed and 94 injured in a [[truck bomb]] attack outside a synagogue in the diamond-trading centre of [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]] in the [[1981 Antwerp bombing]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Jewish Targets: Recent Attacks | url = http://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/07/world/jewish-targets-recent-attacks.html | publisher = The New York Times | date = 1986-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = 2 Killed By Bomb at Antwerp Synagogue | url = http://www.nytimes.com/1981/10/21/world/2-killed-by-bomb-at-antwerp-synagogue.html | publisher = The New York Times | date = 1981-10-21 | first=Paul | last=Lewis}}</ref>
